  "prompt": "What is a ionic bond? What are some examples?",
  "response": "An ionic bond is a type of chemical bond that occurs between two atoms when one atom donates one or more of its electrons to another atom, leading to the formation of oppositely charged ions. This transfer of electrons creates cations (positively charged ions) and anions (negatively charged ions). The electrostatic attraction between these oppositely charged ions results in the formation of the ionic bond.\n\nIonic bonds typically form between metals and non-metals. Metals, which have lower electronegativities, tend to lose electrons and form cations, while non-metals, which have higher electronegativities, tend to gain electrons and form anions.\n\n**Examples of ionic bonds:**\n\n1. **Sodium Chloride (NaCl)**: Sodium (Na) donates one electron to chlorine (Cl), resulting in a sodium ion (Na\u207a) and a chloride ion (Cl\u207b). The attraction between these ions forms table salt.\n\n2. **Magnesium Oxide (MgO)**: Magnesium (Mg) loses two electrons to become Mg\u00b2\u207a, while oxygen (O) gains two electrons to become O\u00b2\u207b. This results in the formation of magnesium oxide.\n\n3. **Calcium Fluoride (CaF\u2082)**: Calcium (Ca) loses two electrons to form Ca\u00b2\u207a ions, and two fluorine (F) atoms each gain one electron to form two F\u207b ions. The electrostatic attraction between Ca\u00b2\u207a and F\u207b leads to the formation of calcium fluoride.\n\n4. **Potassium Bromide (KBr)**: Potassium (K) donates one electron to bromine (Br), resulting in the formation of K\u207a and Br\u207b ions, which bond to form potassium bromide.\n\nThese ionic compounds often form crystal lattice structures, which contribute to their characteristic properties, such as high melting and boiling points, and their ability to conduct electricity when dissolved in water or molten.",
